V. 1 At, quo usque se extendat privatorum in pacis- cendo potestas, difficilior inspectio est. Quod publicum est, a privato alienari non posse satis constat: nam si ne ducibus quidem belli id permissum est, ut modo probavimus, multo minus privatis. Sed de ipsorum actionibus ac rebus quaeri potest, quia videntur haec quoque concedi hostibus non posse sine aliquo damno partis: unde videri possunt talia pacta illicita cum civibus ob jus supereminens civitatis, tum conductis militibus ob fidem sacramento datam.

V. 1 How far the power of private personS, to make agreements, extends, is a more difficult question. That what is public property cannot be alienated by a private person, is sufficiently plain: for if that was not even permitted to generals, as we have proved just nOW, much less is it to private persons. But it may be questioned concern- ing their own actions and property3 because it may seem that these also cannot be eonceded to the enemy without some damage of the party: whence it may seem that such paets with the enemy are unlawful for citizens, on account of the eminent jurisdiction of the state3 and for regular soldiers, on account of their military oath.
